ary Lineker.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/06/claudio-ranieri-leicester-city-title-favourites-manchester-city\">Claudio Ranieri: Leicester City’s spirit is the best I have ever known</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>Aren’t you forgetting </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/kasabian\" title=\"\"><strong>Kasabian</strong></a><strong>?</strong> Nope. But now Leicester is world-famous. Firstly because the body of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/richard-iii\" title=\"\">Richard III was discovered under a car park there</a>, then reburied on 26 March 2015. Secondly, because the local football team, Leicester City, are living through what could become the greatest story in the history of English football.</p> <p><strong>Seriously?</strong> Seriously. On 21 March 2015, Leicester lost to Tottenham Hotspur and were distant last in the Premier League, having won four of their first 29 games. Then, out of nowhere, they won seven of their last nine to achieve an <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014%E2%80%9315_Leicester_City_F.C._season\" title=\"\">incredible escape from relegation</a>.</p> <p><strong>Well done Leicester!</strong> And it doesn’t end there. The summer began disastrously, when the club’s Thai owners took the squad on tour to Thailand, only for a <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/leicester-city-racist-orgy-video-5794654\" title=\"\">video to emerge</a> showing three youth players verbally abusing a group of sex workers during an orgy. One of the men was James Pearson, son of the team’s manager, Nigel, who was <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/11682068/Leicester-City-trio-sacked-over-racist-orgy.html\" title=\"\">sacked soon afterwards</a>. Then in August one of their best players, Jamie Vardy, was videoed shouting <a href=\"http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/6581386/England-ace-Jamie-Vardy-in-racism-storm.html\" title=\"\">angry, racist insults at a man in a casino</a>.</p> <p><strong>Cripes.</strong> However … under their new manager, a likable old pro called <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/jul/14/claudio-ranieri-leicester-city-nigel-pearson\" title=\"\">Claudio Ranieri</a>, Leicester City have risen to the top of the Premier League. After their <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/06/manchester-city-leicester-city-premier-league-match-report\" title=\"\">3-1 victory over Manchester City on Saturday</a>, they are now favourites to win the league, something the club has never done in its 132-year history. Vardy, who was still playing non-league football when he was 25, is now <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/top-scorers\" title=\"\">top of the goalscoring table</a>, and has set a new Premier League record for scoring in successive games.</p> <p><strong>Amazing. So you’re saying that the Leicester City team </strong><a href=\"https://twitter.com/oilysailor/status/693090940668485632\" title=\"\"><strong>miraculously improved from the moment that Richard III was reburied</strong></a><strong>?</strong> I am. And you’ll never guess the name of their stadium, taken from their Thai owners and printed on their shirts.</p> <p><strong>What?</strong> King Power.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> “They’ll make a movie out of this!”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “They might want to skip the racism and orgies.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"11238840","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2016-02-09T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2452494","internalRevision":"108","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"The city’s football team are on the brink of a Premier League miracle – do they have Richard III to thank?","allowUgc":"false","lang":"en","headline":"The incredible resurrection of Leicester","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"